					<description><![CDATA[<p>Mayo Clinic researcher&nbsp;Fergus Couch, Ph.D.,&nbsp;has spent his career studying inherited&nbsp;breast cancer&nbsp;and cancer genetics. Early on, he saw that many families lived with uncertainty of their cancer risk, especially when genetic tests revealed variants no one fully understood.&nbsp; He set out to change that.&amp;#160;&amp;#160; Dr. Couch&amp;#160;is&amp;#160;a&amp;#160;consultant&amp;#160;in&amp;#160;laboratory medicine and pathology&amp;#160;at&amp;#160;the&amp;#160;Mayo Clinic Comprehensive Cancer Center&amp;#160;and holds the Zbigniew [&amp;#8230;]</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/discussion/mayo-clinic-researcher-brings-new-clarity-to-breast-cancer-risk-through-genetics-research/">Mayo Clinic&nbsp;researcher&nbsp;brings new clarity to breast cancer risk through genetics research&nbsp;</a> appeared first on <a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org">Mayo Clinic News Network</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="450" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Fergus-Couch-PhD-microscope_16x9.jpg" alt="Dr. Fergus Couch sitting at a microscope" class="wp-image-349652" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Fergus-Couch-PhD-microscope_16x9.jpg 800w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Fergus-Couch-PhD-microscope_16x9-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Fergus-Couch-PhD-microscope_16x9-768x432.jpg 768w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Fergus Couch, Ph.D.</figcaption></figure>



<p>Mayo Clinic researcher&nbsp;<a href="https://www.mayo.edu/research/faculty/couch-fergus-j-ph-d/bio-00027515" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Fergus Couch, Ph.D.</a>,&nbsp;has spent his career studying inherited&nbsp;<a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/breast-cancer/symptoms-causes/syc-20352470" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">breast cancer</a>&nbsp;and cancer genetics. Early on, he saw that many families lived with uncertainty of their cancer risk, especially when genetic tests revealed variants no one fully understood.&nbsp;</p>



<p>He set out to change that.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>Dr. Couch&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;a&amp;nbsp;consultant&amp;nbsp;in&amp;nbsp;laboratory medicine and pathology&amp;nbsp;at&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;<a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/departments-centers/mayo-clinic-cancer-center" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mayo Clinic Comprehensive Cancer Center</a>&amp;nbsp;and holds the Zbigniew and Anna M. Scheller Professorship in Medical Research in Honor of Dr. Thomas J. McDonald.&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>Mayo Clinic works with an international network of collaborators, which includes Dr. Couch and his team,&amp;nbsp;who have&amp;nbsp;helped&amp;nbsp;identify&amp;nbsp;many inherited gene alterations that contribute to breast cancer risk.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;</p>


<div class="wp-block-image is-style-center-align-caption">
<figure class="alignright size-full is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="857" height="857" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/12/Fergus-Couch-Ph.D.-1554072_3786066_0018-1x1-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-409119" style="width:239px;height:auto" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/12/Fergus-Couch-Ph.D.-1554072_3786066_0018-1x1-1.jpg 857w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/12/Fergus-Couch-Ph.D.-1554072_3786066_0018-1x1-1-300x300.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/12/Fergus-Couch-Ph.D.-1554072_3786066_0018-1x1-1-150x150.jpg 150w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/12/Fergus-Couch-Ph.D.-1554072_3786066_0018-1x1-1-768x768.jpg 768w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 857px) 100vw, 857px" /></figure>
</div>


<p>"We interact on a thematic level — surgeons, oncologists, pathologists, geneticists and biochemists," Dr. Couch shares. "We all work together, focused on improving our knowledge of breast cancer and quickly developing treatments and cures for patients at Mayo Clinic."&nbsp;</p>



<p>Earlier this year,&nbsp;Dr. Couch and other co-authors&nbsp;published&nbsp;a study in&nbsp;<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-08388-8" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Nature</a>,&nbsp;which&nbsp;included&nbsp;one of the most comprehensive functional maps to date of the BRCA2 cancer risk gene.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>By testing&amp;nbsp;nearly every&amp;nbsp;possible change&amp;nbsp;in this gene, Mayo Clinic researchers can&amp;nbsp;identify&amp;nbsp;which patients are more likely to&amp;nbsp;benefit&amp;nbsp;from targeted cancer therapies.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>The work reclassifies previously uncertain genetic test results, helping care teams individualize cancer screening,&amp;nbsp;prevention&amp;nbsp;and treatment. Together, it shows how Mayo Clinic is turning complex genetic data into information clinicians can use now, a central goal of&amp;nbsp;precision medicine.&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>"It's the extra step that makes the difference, helping people use the findings immediately," Dr. Couch says. "The results of our paper&amp;nbsp;are used to help patients in the clinic. My entire career has been focused on getting information to patients as quickly as possible."&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>Today, Dr. Couch continues to explore why certain inherited changes lead to cancer, why some families develop breast cancer without known risk&amp;nbsp;genes&amp;nbsp;and how discoveries in the lab can&amp;nbsp;translate&amp;nbsp;to improved&amp;nbsp;care.&amp;nbsp;Just this month,&amp;nbsp;Dr. Couch won the prestigious Komen&amp;nbsp;Brinker Award for Scientific Distinction in Basic Science&amp;nbsp;for his significant work in advancing breast cancer research.&amp;nbsp;</p>



